8 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 8. (a) Subject to subsections (b) and (c), unless
9 barred by section 6 or 7 of this chapter, an anatomical gift of a
10 decedent's body or part for the purpose of transplantation, therapy,
11 research, or education may be made by any member of the following
12 classes of persons who are reasonably available, in the order of priority
13 listed:
14 (1) An agent of the decedent at the time of death who could have
15 made an anatomical gift under section 3(2) of this chapter
16 immediately before the decedent's death.
17 (2) The spouse of the decedent.
18 (3) Adult children of the decedent.
19 (4) Parents of the decedent.
20 (5) Adult siblings of the decedent.
21 (6) A guardian appointed by a court under IC 29-3-5-3.
22 (7) Adult grandchildren of the decedent.
23 (8) Grandparents of the decedent.
24 (9) An adult who exhibited special care and concern for the
25 decedent.
26 (10) Any other person having the authority to dispose of the
27 decedent's body.
28 (a) Except as provided in subsections (b) and (d), and unless
29 barred by section 6 or 7 of this chapter, the following persons, in
30 the priority indicated, have the authority to make an anatomical
31 gift with respect to a decedent, including the manner, purpose, and
32 scope of the anatomical gift:
33 (1) A person:
34 (A) granted the authority to serve in a funeral planning
35 declaration executed by the decedent under IC 29-2-19; or
36 (B) named in a United States Department of Defense form
37 "Record of Emergency Data" (DD Form 93) or a successor
38 form adopted by the United States Department of Defense,
39 if the decedent died while serving in any branch of the
40 United States Armed Forces (as defined in 10 U.S.C. 101)
41 and completed the form.
42 (2) An agent of the decedent.
